b'[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe01121.htm)  [Next](sbe01123.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n[Buy this Book at\nAmazon.com](http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B002DEMBW6/internetsacredte)\n\n* * *\n\n[![](../../img/tn_hin.jpg)](index.htm)  \n_The Upanishads, Part 1 (SBE01)_ , by Max Muller, [1879], at sacred-texts.com\n\n* * *\n\n### FOURTH KHA _N_ _D_ A.\n\n1\\. \'The red colour of burning fire (agni) is the colour of fire, the white\ncolour of fire is the colour of water, the black colour of fire the colour of\nearth. Thus vanishes what we call fire, as a mere variety, being a name,\narising from speech. What is true (satya) are the three colours (or forms).\n\n2\\. \'The red colour of the sun (aditya) is the colour of fire, the white of\nwater, the black of earth. Thus vanishes what we call the sun, as a mere\nvariety, being a name, arising from speech. What is true are the three\ncolours.\n\n3\\. \'The red colour of the moon is the colour of fire, the white of water, the\nblack of earth. Thus vanishes what we call the moon, as a mere variety, being\na name, arising from speech. What is true are the three colours.\n\n4\\. \'The red colour of the lightning is the colour of fire, the white of\nwater, the black of earth. Thus\n\np. 96\n\nvanishes what we call the lightning, as a mere variety, being a name, arising\nfrom speech. What is true are the three colours.\n\n5\\. \'Great householders and great theologians of olden times who knew this,\nhave declared the same, saying, "No one can henceforth mention to us anything\nwhich we have not heard, perceived, or known 1." Out of these (three colours\nor forms) they knew all.\n\n6\\. \'Whatever they thought looked red, they knew was the colour of fire.\nWhatever they thought looked white, they knew was the colour of water.\nWhatever they thought looked black, they knew was the colour of earth.\n\n7\\. \'Whatever they thought was altogether unknown, they knew was some\ncombination of those three beings (devata).\n\n\'Now learn from me, my friend, how those three beings, when they reach man,\nbecome each of them tripartite.\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[96:1](sbe01122.htm#fr_281) This reminds one of the Aristotelian \xce\xb4\xce\xb9\xe1\xbd\xb0 \xce\xb3\xe1\xbd\xb0\xcf\x81 \xcf\x84\xce\xb1\xe1\xbf\xa6\xcf\x84\xce\xb1\n\xce\xba\xce\xb1\xe1\xbd\xb6 \xe1\xbc\x90\xce\xba \xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xe1\xbd\xbb\xcf\x84\xcf\x89\xce\xbd \xcf\x84\xe1\xbc\x84\xce\xbb\xce\xbb\xce\xb1 \xce\xb3\xce\xbd\xcf\x89\xcf\x81\xce\xaf\xce\xb6\xce\xb5\xcf\x84\xce\xb1\xce\xb9, \xe1\xbc\x80\xce\xbb\xce\xbb\xe1\xbe\xbd \xce\xbf\xe1\xbd\x90 \xcf\x84\xce\xb1\xe1\xbf\xa6\xcf\x84\xce\xb1 \xce\xb4\xce\xb9\xe1\xbd\xb0 \xcf\x84\xe1\xbf\xb6\xce\xbd \xe1\xbd\x91\xcf\x80\xce\xbf\xce\xba\xce\xb5\xce\xb9\xce\xbc\xe1\xbd\xb3\xce\xbd\xcf\x89\xce\xbd.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: VI, 5](sbe01123.htm)\n\n'